<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="698" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d698">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1976</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-23">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 23, 1915, noon</hi>.</date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.15 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2617. Wolff’s Bureau sends out semi-officially notice that Germans
                                working in America on war material for Allies make themselves <pb facs="0743" n="485" xml:id="pg_485"/> liable to prosecution for
                                treason as soon as they touch German soil.</p>
                            <p>The hate campaign against America continues with unabated violence,
                                backed, I am convinced, by <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">Von
                                    Tirpitz</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RECZ1">Reventlow</persName> and company, who seem to desire war with
                                America.</p>
                            <p>Although I have advocated concessions to preserve peace, I am now
                                convinced that no concession that we make short of joining Germany
                                in war will satisfy this extreme party which seems for the present
                                in control.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>